<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=102735465454774></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f102735465454774><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=102735465454774>RE: Agro</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=102735465454774#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=123346><span id= >quintis</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>2 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Jul 22nd 12:30 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>With aggro control for the enchanter, there are 3 main points to consider<br><br>* Aggro preparation - <br>a) Before boss engagement, 3 spells can be used to prepare for (hopefully) predictable aggro<br>-&gt; Horrifying visage/beguling visage - the seemingly obvious choice - cast bvisage on yourself and hvisage on main tank. The fact that they have very long recast delays and high mana cost compared to how long they last is why they are not as good as they appear to be. The most practical way to use these spells is to have multiple enchanters coordinating chain horrifying the main tank (ex Enc A - horrify, 20 secs later Enc B horrify, etc etc) and each enc beguile before debuffing...<br>-&gt; Tricksters Augmentation - Imp form has the DD proc which also adds aggro per hit. Like Boon, this spell needs a dedicated slot. My personal choice to cast on main tank. <br>b) In a high end raid situation with multiple enchanters (or even shamana who we share debuff effects with), organize it so that the debuffs are spread out (ex. enchanter A - Tash, enchanter B -slow etc etc). <br><br>* Aggro management in battle -<br>a) As simple as it sounds, waiting for the main tank(s) in a raid situation to generate aggro and seeing their &quot;Engage mobs now&quot; text is something enchanters have to learn. Considering an xp grind battle can last 2 min and a boss battle can last 20 min, its easy to see why it gets tempting to debuff early on when seeing the main tank with 3000 hp go to half life in 30 secs.<br>b) There are a couple spells to possibly help with this in battle<br>-&gt; Root<br>-&gt; Blind - blind causes a mob to either run away in fear OR hit only those in melee range. The downsides is that its resistable, is a decent aggro maker in its own right and is a surprise to people who have never seen it in action.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>-&gt; Reoccuring Amnesia - this is my most trusted mem blur - and it works as an aggro reducer NOT and aggro eraser. Ex - if a Tash generates 200 points of aggro , reoccuring amnesia removes 100 points, the taunting paladin generates 300 points of aggro  - and the mob forgets about me. Its a bit more complicated than that, but for our purposes you see how this tool can be used . However, different monsters will have different aggro score schemes. <br>c) As a side note - Dispelling and Mana Seive are generally not aggro producing. Torment of Argli, the definitive mana drainer, however, counts as DoT.<br>d) Stagger some time between your debuffs to allow the main tank to maintain aggro.<br><br>* Aggro survival &amp; acceptance -<br>No matter what you do or if things go wrong, you will get aggro. Its part of the enchanter life. What to do?<br>a) Invest in HP/AC gear - Yes as casters we dont get the best AC and HP in the game - but the goal for pushing AC/HP is not to tank monsters but to survive long enough for that saving spell (heal, mezz etc etc) I have been in situations where less than 100hp for me personally was the difference between raid wipeout and success. As you get higher in level or if you know you arent in mezzing, sacrificing charisma gear for hp/ac gear is a possible choice.<br>b) Learn to love your pet again - With the changes in pets, the animation becomes a formidable bodyguard. Specifically for this writing, the level 49 and 55 animation both taunt, and can inflict enough dmg or aggro to get the mob of you - that is if your raid allows or trusts you enough to use one.<br>c) HP shields - since you know you are going to get aggro - why not prepare for it - stacking Rune and Bezerk Spirit line can add a significant amount of HP and can be used as a pseudo heal - my current favorite is Rune V and Bedlam. Be aware that there are spells which they dont stack with, which I believe are the cleric HP spells (rune) and strength spells (Bedlam)<br>d) Invest AA points into spell casting subtlety - the AA skill which reduces aggro generated by spells<br><br>* Smart Self Sacrifice - <br>Some mobs or situations demand initial debuffing and subsequent death - accept it. One excellent example is Trakanon (sp) - a single group with a warrior,cleric and enchanter can make it easier for an entire raid. The warrior &amp; cleric can buy enough time for the enchanter to dispell, Tash, and maybe a torment of Argli before they eat Trak's initial AoE poison breath...<br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Mon Jul 22 12:36:53 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Quintis<br>58 Enchanter<br>Druzzil Ro</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
